ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Washington Post article is a very sobering look at what is going on in Pakistan, where it is clear the anti-vaccination movement is taking an aggressive position in the country and using old suspicions as well as new fake events to further scare parents away from vaccinating their children. As the article points out, there is a mix of old with new technology, using social media to amplify the scare tactics and sabotage vaccination efforts.

There seems to be a clear role for the assistance of medical anthropologists who can provide guidance in how to overcome this fear mongering and return the country to the former path approaching eradication of the disease with interruption of transmission of the WPV.

A very disturbing observation is the former report we posted stating that there was 95 percent coverage of the target population with the polio vaccine during the April 2019 vaccination campaign in the country (see Poliomyelitis update (34): global (Pakistan, Niger), follow-up 20190509.6462140). The reports strongly suggest that the coverage in KP was significantly lower than 95 percent, leading to concerns rather than optimism about the march towards eradication. - Mod.MPP

Despite great differences in geography and culture, there are some shared aspects in the community resistance to the polio vaccination campaign in Pakistan and the Ebola control efforts in northeast Congo. For the latter, see, for example: https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/05/10/721020887/threats-by-text-a-mob-outside-the-door-what-health-workers-face-in-the-ebola-zon.

In both situations, individuals or organized groups have exploited local disease ignorance and distrust of national authorities to foment violence against public health teams. This misinformation and distrust have culminated in otherwise unfathomable destruction of healthcare clinics and murders of healthcare workers. As highlighted in the articles above, local people naturally become suspicious about the singular attention devoted to only one disease, using resources that are visibly funded by foreign agencies. Meanwhile, they perceive that the government neglects their basic needs and their children continue to die of preventable diseases, such as malaria and cholera, which don't enjoy the international attention devoted to polio and Ebola. Perhaps, indeed, a radical rethink of disease control strategies is overdue, one that takes into account the broader health needs and priorities of the local population. - Mod.LXL]
